`,e.jsx(n.p,{children:"If a given RegionServer has 16 GB of RAM, with default settings, the formula works out to 16384*0.4/128 ~ 51 regions per RS is a starting point. The formula can be extended to multiple tables; if they all have the same configuration, just use the total number of families."}),`
`,e.jsx(n.p,{children:"This number can be adjusted; the formula above assumes all your regions are filled at approximately the same rate. If only a fraction of your regions are going to be actively written to, you can divide the result by that fraction to get a larger region count. Then, even if all regions are written to, all region memstores are not filled evenly, and eventually jitter appears even if they are (due to limited number of concurrent flushes). Thus, one can have as many as 2-3 times more regions than the starting point; however, increased numbers carry increased risk."}),`
`,e.jsx(n.p,{children:"For write-heavy workload, memstore fraction can be increased in configuration at the expense of block cache; this will also allow one to have more regions."}),`
`,e.jsx(n.h4,{id:"number-of-regions-per-rs---lower-bound",children:"Number of regions per RS - lower bound"}),`
`,e.jsx(n.p,{children:"HBase scales by having regions across many servers. Thus if you have 2 regions for 16GB data, on a 20 node machine your data will be concentrated on just a few machines - nearly the entire cluster will be idle. This really can't be stressed enough, since a common problem is loading 200MB data into HBase and then wondering why your awesome 10 node cluster isn't doing anything."}),`
`,e.jsx(n.p,{children:"On the other hand, if you have a very large amount of data, you may also want to go for a larger number of regions to avoid having regions that are too large."}),`
`,e.jsx(n.h4,{id:"maximum-region-size",children:"Maximum region size"}),`
`,e.jsx(n.p,{children:"For large tables in production scenarios, maximum region size is mostly limited by compactions - very large compactions, esp. major, can degrade cluster performance. Currently, the recommended maximum region size is 10-20Gb, and 5-10Gb is optimal. For older 0.90.x codebase, the upper-bound of regionsize is about 4Gb, with a default of 256Mb."}),`
`,e.jsxs(n.p,{children:["The size at which the region is split into two is generally configured via ",e.jsx(n.a,{href:"/docs/configuration/default#hbasehregionmaxfilesize-toc",children:"hbase.hregion.max.filesize"}),"; for details, see ",e.jsx(n.a,{href:"/docs/architecture/regions#region-splits",children:"arch.region.splits"}),"."]}),`
`,e.jsx(n.p,{children:"If you cannot estimate the size of your tables well, when starting off, it's probably best to stick to the default region size, perhaps going smaller for hot tables (or manually split hot regions to spread the load over the cluster), or go with larger region sizes if your cell sizes tend to be largish (100k and up)."}),`
`,e.jsxs(n.p,{children:["In HBase 0.98, experimental stripe compactions feature was added that would allow for larger regions, especially for log data. See ",e.jsx(n.a,{href:"/docs/architecture/regions#experimental-stripe-compactions",children:"ops.stripe"}),"."]}),`
`,e.jsx(n.h4,{id:"total-data-size-per-region-server",children:"Total data size per region server"}),`
`,e.jsx(n.p,{children:"According to above numbers for region size and number of regions per region server, in an optimistic estimate 10 GB x 100 regions per RS will give up to 1TB served per region server, which is in line with some of the reported multi-PB use cases. However, it is important to think about the data vs cache size ratio at the RS level. With 1TB of data per server and 10 GB block cache, only 1% of the data will be cached, which may barely cover all block indices."}),`
